 thriving Little Italy, on the other hand, drew Italians together from across the wider region. These distinctive ethnic enclaves, Stanger-Ross argues, were shaped by each city’s response to suburbanization, segregation, and economic restructuring. By situating malleable ethnic bonds in the context of political economy and racial dynamics, he offers a fresh perspective on the potential of local environments to shape individual identities and social experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEthnic neighborhoodszCanadaxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aEthnic neighborhoodszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aEthnicityzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aEthnicityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aItalian AmericanszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxEthnic identityxHistoryy20th century. 0aItalianszOntariozTorontoxEthnic identityxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226770765423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226770765.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles